## Phase 2 — Authentication Layer

### API Endpoints to Consume
| Action | Web Route | Mobile Call |
|--------|-----------|-------------|
| Login | `POST /api/auth/signin` | `POST /api/auth/credentials` |
| Register | `POST /api/auth/register` | Same |
| Session check | `GET /api/auth/session` | Same (include cookie/token) |

> [!NOTE]
> NextAuth v5 uses cookies for session. The mobile app will need to handle session tokens manually via `expo-secure-store` and send a `Cookie` or `Authorization` header on every request.
>
> **Recommended:** Add a dedicated `POST /api/mobile/login` route to the Next.js app that returns a signed JWT the mobile client stores locally. This avoids the cookie complexity.

### 2.1 Auth Store (Zustand)
```ts
// store/auth-store.ts
interface AuthState {
  token: string | null;
  user: { id: string; name: string; email: string } | null;
  householdId: string | null;
  login: (token: string, user: User) => void;
  logout: () => void;
}
```

### 2.2 Login Screen
- Email + Password fields
- "Sign In" button with loading state
- Link to Register
- Show error toasts via `react-native-toast-message`

### 2.3 Root Layout Auth Guard
```tsx
// app/_layout.tsx
const { token } = useAuthStore();
if (!token) return <Redirect href="/(auth)/login" />;
```

---

## Phase 3 — Shared API Client

```ts
// lib/api-client.ts
const BASE_URL = process.env.EXPO_PUBLIC_API_URL; // https://budgetcap.vercel.app

export async function apiFetch<T>(
  path: string,
  options?: RequestInit
): Promise<T> {
  const token = await SecureStore.getItemAsync("session_token");
  const res = await fetch(`${BASE_URL}${path}`, {
    ...options,
    headers: {
      "Content-Type": "application/json",
      Authorization: `Bearer ${token}`,
      ...options?.headers,
    },
  });
  if (!res.ok) throw new APIError(res.status, await res.json());
  return res.json();
}
```

