## Phased Delivery Timeline

| Phase | Deliverable | Effort |
|-------|-------------|--------|
| 1 | Project bootstrap + NativeWind configured | 1–2h |
| 2 | Auth screens (Login, Register) + token storage | 2–3h |
| 3 | API client + React Query setup | 1–2h |
| 4 | Dashboard / Budget tab (core feature) | 4–6h |
| 5 | Transactions tab + Add Transaction sheet | 4–5h |
| 6 | Accounts tab | 2–3h |
| 7 | Reports tab (charts) | 3–4h |
| 8 | Settings + Envelope management | 2–3h |
| 9 | Polish: animations, haptics, error states | 2–3h |
| 10 | EAS build + deploy to TestFlight / Play Store | 1–2h |

**Total estimated effort: ~22–33 hours**

---

## Key Decisions & Trade-offs

> [!NOTE]
> **Why Expo Router v3?** File-based routing mirrors the Next.js App Router the web app already uses — same mental model, easier context switching.

> [!TIP]
> **NativeWind v4** uses the Tailwind compiler at build time, so class names are resolved to StyleSheet objects — no runtime overhead.

> [!WARNING]
> **Prisma cannot run on the mobile device.** All DB access must go through the Next.js API. The mobile app is a pure client.

> [!CAUTION]
> NextAuth v5 cookie sessions are httpOnly and not accessible from a native app's HTTP client. A dedicated JWT-based mobile auth endpoint must be added to the Next.js backend before the mobile app can authenticate.
